root_causes: Script references B2cDKx1 but expected variable is the checkbox indicator B2cDKx1_99.
Validation is applied to the wrong variable name (so it won't check the '99' checkbox field).
instructions: Change all occurrences of B2cDKx1 to B2cDKx1_99 in the sel and list statements.

Keep the existing check for code 99 (sel if miss(B2cDKx1_99) or ~range(B2cDKx1_99,99,99)) if the _99 variable stores the answer code directly; if the checkbox is coded 0/1 use sel if miss(B2cDKx1_99) or B2cDKx1_99 <> 1 instead.

root_causes: Script references B2cDKx1 (the base multi variable) but the expected Variable ID is B2cDKx1_99 (the specific indicator/other-code variable).

The check any(B2cDKx1,99) assumes a multi-response stored as codes in B2cDKx1; if the dataset uses a separate indicator variable B2cDKx1_99 (common for _99 fields), any(...,99) is inappropriate for that indicator.
instructions: Reference the expected variable B2cDKx1_99 instead of B2cDKx1.
If B2cDKx1_99 is an indicator coded 1 when answer code 99 was selected, change the selection to: sel if miss(B2cDKx1_99) or B2cDKx1_99 <> 1 (or sel if miss(B2cDKx1_99) or ~range(B2cDKx1_99,1,1)).

If instead the multi-response is stored in a single variable named B2cDKx1 that contains code 99 when selected, keep any(B2cDKx1,99) but ensure the expected Variable ID in documentation is corrected to B2cDKx1.

root_causes: Script references B2cDKx2 (the base multi variable) but the expected Variable ID is B2cDKx2_99 (the specific indicator/other-code variable).
The any(B2cDKx2,99) approach may be incorrect if an indicator variable B2cDKx2_99 exists (any() is not the right check for a 0/1 indicator).
instructions: Reference B2cDKx2_99 instead of B2cDKx2.
If B2cDKx2_99 is an indicator coded 1 when code 99 was selected, use: sel if miss(B2cDKx2_99) or B2cDKx2_99 <> 1 (or sel if miss(B2cDKx2_99) or ~range(B2cDKx2_99,1,1)).
If the data actually store selections in B2cDKx2 as codes (including 99), either update the expected Variable ID to B2cDKx2 or keep any(B2cDKx2,99).

instructions: Use B2cDKx3_99 in the selection expression instead of B2cDKx3.
If B2cDKx3_99 is an indicator variable coded 1 when the 99 option was chosen, change to: sel if miss(B2cDKx3_99) or B2cDKx3_99 <> 1 (or sel if miss(B2cDKx3_99) or ~range(B2cDKx3_99,1,1)).
If selections are stored in B2cDKx3 as codes (including 99), reconcile the expected Variable ID to B2cDKx3 and keep any(B2cDKx3,99).

root_causes: Script references B2cDKx4 rather than the expected indicator variable B2cDKx4_99.
The any(B2cDKx4,99) construct may not correctly validate an indicator _99 variable (which would require a direct comparison to 1).
instructions: Replace references to B2cDKx4 with B2cDKx4_99 in the SPSS selection.
If B2cDKx4_99 is an indicator (1=selected), use: sel if miss(B2cDKx4_99) or B2cDKx4_99 <> 1 (or sel if miss(B2cDKx4_99) or ~range(B2cDKx4_99,1,1)).
If instead the multi-response codes are stored in B2cDKx4 (with code 99), either update the expected Variable ID to B2cDKx4 or keep the any(B2cDKx4,99) check.
